            <li><strong>Steady Demand:</strong> UAE's multinational population creates constant need for certified translation</li>
            <li><strong>Professional Recognition:</strong> MOJ certification represents the highest translation credential in the UAE</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-section">
          <details class="faq-item" name="faq">
            <summary>How long does the MOJ certification process take?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>From application to license, expect 2-4 months. This includes document verification, scheduling the examination, and processing after you pass. The examination itself may have waiting periods depending on Ministry schedules.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item" name="faq">
            <summary>What are the MOJ translator exam fees?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Application and examination fees are set by the Ministry of Justice and may change. Check the current fee schedule on the MOJ website or at a service center. Budget for initial licensing and annual renewal fees.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item" name="faq">
            <summary>Can I work as a translator without MOJ certification?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Yes, but with limitations. Non-MOJ translators can work on content that doesn't require court or government submission—marketing materials, websites, business communications. However, any translation destined for courts, ministries, or official government use requires MOJ certification.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item" name="faq">
            <summary>Is the exam difficult?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Candidates with strong bilingual abilities and legal knowledge typically pass. Those without legal background or with weaker language skills may struggle. Adequate preparation—especially studying UAE legal terminology—significantly improves pass rates.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item" name="faq">
            <summary>Can foreign-qualified translators work in UAE?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>Foreign translation credentials aren't directly recognized. You must pass the UAE MOJ examination regardless of qualifications elsewhere. However, experience and training from abroad will help you prepare for the exam.</p>
            </div>
          </details>

          <details class="faq-item" name="faq">
            <summary>What languages can I get certified for?</summary>
            <div class="faq-answer">
              <p>The MOJ licenses translators for specific language pairs. Arabic-English is most common, but certification is available for other languages including French, German, Russian, Urdu, and others based on demand and examiner availability.</p>
            </div>
          </details>
        </div>

